@GretaThunberg has arrived in New York City, marking the end of her 15-day, 3,000 mile voyage across the Atlantic on a zero-carbon yacht.

She was met by crowds of supporters and a flotilla of sailing boats, each with a sustainable development goal written on its sails.

Greta refused to fly to the US to attend a UN climate summit next month because of the carbon emissions caused by planes. She set sail from Plymouth in southern England on 14 August. 'It was a bit rough sometimes but it went incredibly well, and I didn't feel seasick, so I was extremely lucky,' she told reporters.

@Stormzy has confirmed that he will fund two more Cambridge students in the next academic year.

The 26-year-old grime artist, who headlined this year's Glastonbury, set up the Stormzy Scholarship last year to offer financial support to people from minority backgrounds who have earned their place at Cambridge. The aim? To address the relatively low number of minority ethnic students who attend Oxbridge institutions.

The identities of the students supported by the scheme have been kept secret to make sure they have a normal life during their studies, although Stormzy keeps track of their academic progress.

@gretathunberg has hit back after Australian News Corp columnist Andrew Bolt took aim at the 16-year-old campaigner, dismissing her followers as members of a cult and disparaging her decision to sail across the Atlantic to attend the UN climate summits.

